{{!-- FAQ --}}
<section id="faq">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="eyebrow">FAQ</div>
    <h2 style="max-width: 640px;">Common questions, answered.</h2>

    <div class="faq">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div>
          <h3>Why not just drag and drop in Finder?</h3>
          <p>You can. But Finder won't sanitize filenames for FAT32, won't skip files you've already copied, won't show progress on slow USB writes, and won't read your Apple Music library directly.</p>
          <p>Conduxor handles all of that so you don't have to.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div>
          <h3>Which devices does it work with?</h3>
          <p>Shokz OpenSwim and OpenSwim Pro are the primary targets. Conduxor also works with any USB audio device that mounts as a FAT32 flash drive, like older iPods in mass-storage mode or generic MP3 players.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div>
          <h3>Will it work with my Apple Music subscription tracks?</h3>
          <p>It works with any track in your Apple Music library that's actually a file on your Mac, like purchased music, ripped CDs, or downloaded files.</p>
          <p>Streaming-only Apple Music tracks (which are DRM-protected) can't be copied to a USB device by any app, including Conduxor. If you've downloaded an Apple Music track for offline play, that's still a streaming file under the hood and it won't transfer.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div>
          <h3>What if my device doesn't show up?</h3>
          <p>Try unplugging and replugging the cable, and confirm the device appears in Finder's sidebar. If Finder sees it but Conduxor doesn't, email me and I'll help you sort it out.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

